data.content:
Here are the better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0) →
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)) →
    Assert.That.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3) →
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null) →
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(x)` | Clear failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.All(...))` | `Assert.That.AllSatisfy(...)` | Reports *which* item failed |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Explicit null-check semantics |

The `CollectionAssert.That` and `Assert.That` APIs are available in **MSTest v3.8+**. For older versions, `CollectionAssert.AreEqual`, `CollectionAssert.Contains`, and `Assert.AreEqual` are the main alternatives.
